6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 IT Asset Catalog
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a current IT Asset Catalog in the System of Engagement.
 The catalog shall enumerate all hardware models,
 software titles,
 and services that fall within the operational purview of the Information Operations Department,
 regardless of asset support tier as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (IT Asset Management Policy).
 The IT Asset Catalog is an internal operational reference document maintained for IT Department use and shall not be published to general County staff.
 The IT Asset Catalog is a service-support governance register that maps support posture to each hardware model,
 software title,
 and service within the Department's operational purview.
 The IT Asset Catalog shall not be construed as a substitute for the asset inventory maintained under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 or the Configuration Item record maintained under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Configuration Management (CMDB) Policy).
 The IT Director holds sole authority to establish and approve the catalog and its contents.
 The Assistant IT Director shall present the catalog for IT Director review and approval no less than annually and following any significant change to the County's technology environment,
 contract portfolio,
 or vendor relationships.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Asset Lifecycle Status Classifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Every hardware model,
 software title,
 and service enumerated in the IT Asset Catalog shall carry one of the following three lifecycle status classifications.
 These classifications govern the IT Department's support commitment for each item and inform service level obligations as defined in Section 6.4 of this policy.
 Support classification under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 determines ownership and escalation routing for each asset;
 lifecycle status classification under this policy determines the level of support commitment the Department provides.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Supported
\series default
:
 Designates hardware,
 software,
 or services that are fully endorsed and actively supported by the Information Operations Department.
 Supported assets represent the standard authorized technology environment for Elko County.
 The IT Department shall fulfill its full service level commitments for Supported assets as defined in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Deprecated
\series default
:
 Designates hardware,
 software,
 or services that remain operational but have been formally identified for replacement.
 At the time of Deprecated classification,
 the IT Director shall establish and document a mandatory replacement deadline in the IT Asset Catalog.
 Deprecated assets are no longer authorized for new deployments or expanded use.
 The IT Department shall provide support for Deprecated assets within the labor ceiling framework defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.5 for the duration of the replacement window.
 Upon reaching the replacement deadline,
 the Assistant IT Director shall transition the asset to Unsupported status unless the IT Director has formally authorized an extension in writing,
 documented in the IT Asset Catalog with a new deadline and supporting rationale.
 No open-ended extensions shall be granted.
 The IT Director may authorize continued remediation beyond the standard labor ceiling by written notation in the work order,
 in accordance with the disposition review process defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unsupported
\series default
:
 Designates hardware,
 software,
 or services that the Information Operations Department does not support and will not remediate.
 Unsupported assets represent an active operational and security risk and shall be prioritized for immediate replacement or decommissioning under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall close work orders submitted for Unsupported assets with a documented replacement referral.
 The IT Department's obligation for Unsupported assets is limited to documenting the referral and initiating the replacement process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall approve all lifecycle status classifications and reclassifications.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that classification reviews are conducted no less than annually and whenever a vendor announces end-of-life,
 a contract expires,
 a security risk materially changes,
 or a replacement technology is formally adopted.
 The Assistant IT Director shall prepare reclassification proposals,
 document the proposed effective date and supporting rationale,
 and submit them to the IT Director for approval prior to implementation in the IT Asset Catalog.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Triage and Severity Classification Authority
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All work orders submitted to the Information Operations Department shall undergo IT-side triage prior to the commencement of active work.
 User-submitted severity levels represent the requester's assessment and shall be treated as an input to triage,
 not as a binding operational classification.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall confirm or reclassify the severity level based on verified operational impact assessment prior to committing to a service level response.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall document any reclassification in the work order with a brief rationale.
 The operative severity,
 as confirmed or reclassified by the assigned technician or queue reviewer,
 governs all service level commitments defined in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that the assigned technician or queue reviewer completes triage within one (1) business hour of work order submission.
 Triage is complete when the assigned technician or queue reviewer has assessed the work order,
 confirmed or reclassified the severity,
 and initiated or queued the appropriate response.
 Where a submitted work order lacks sufficient information to complete triage,
 the assigned technician or queue reviewer shall document the attempt,
 specify the information required,
 and notify the requester that more information is required.
 Service level clocks shall be paused for the duration of pending information status and shall resume upon receipt of the required information from the requester.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall close work orders that remain in pending information status without requester response for five (5) consecutive business days,
 with closure rationale documented in the work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Service Level Commitments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Service level commitments consist of two sequential obligations:
 a response commitment and a resolution or escalation commitment.
 All timeframes are measured in business hours or business days from the completion of triage unless otherwise specified.
 Business hours are defined as Monday through Friday,
 8:00 AM to 5:00 PM,
 excluding Elko County observed holidays.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that service level commitments are met and shall monitor adherence in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Response and resolution commitments by severity level are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Critical severity
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Response within one (1) business hour of triage completion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
